          "title": "Why Luke tells the conversion three times",
          "body": "Acts narrates the Damascus road three times: ch. 9 (Luke's narration to the reader), ch. 22 (Paul's apologia to Jews), ch. 26 (Paul's apologia to Agrippa and Festus). The repetition is not redundancy — it is theological argumentation. Each retelling foregrounds elements appropriate to the audience. In ch. 9 the Ananias episode includes Christ's command *he is a chosen instrument of Mine, to bear My name before the Gentiles* (9:15) — said *to Ananias*, not yet known to Paul. In ch. 22, addressing Jews, Paul foregrounds Ananias's Torah-piety and locates the Gentile commission in the *temple*. In ch. 26, addressing Romans, Paul collapses Ananias entirely and reports the Gentile commission as said *directly* by the heavenly Christ. The triple telling makes the point Luke wants the reader to land: **the Gentile mission is not a Pauline innovation, not a later development, not a Lukan editorial — it is embedded in the original commission, narratable in three modes for three audiences, and unrejectable across all three.**"
